    "Explain how databases index data<|assistant|A database index is like a book's index - instead of scanning every page, you look up the term and jump to the right page.\n\nWithout index: Full table scan - checks every row (O(n))\nWith index: B-tree lookup - finds rows fast (O(log n))\n\nCREATE INDEX idx_email ON users(email);\n\nWhen to index:\n- Columns used in WHERE clauses\n- Columns used in JOIN conditions\n- Columns used in ORDER BY\n\nWhen NOT to index:\n- Small tables (scan is faster than index lookup)\n- Columns with low cardinality (many duplicates like gender)\n- Tables with heavy writes (each index slows INSERT/UPDATE)\n\nTypes:\n- B-tree: Default, good for equality and range queries\n- Hash: Only equality queries, faster lookups\n- Composite: Multiple columns in one index\n- Unique: Enforces uniqueness + speeds up lookups\n\nThe EXPLAIN command shows if your query uses indexes: EXPLAIN SELECT * FROM users WHERE email = 'test@example.com'",
